From: Your Name <your.email@example.com>
Date: Mon, 02 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] TEST: stop_machine: add debugfs test hooks for deadlock
 detection validation

DO NOT MERGE — test/validation only patch.
Apply ON TOP of the deadlock detection patch.

This patch adds three test mechanisms to validate that the deadlock
detection code in multi_cpu_stop() works correctly without needing to
reproduce the actual race condition:

TEST 1: debugfs "dump_only" trigger
  Write any value to:
    /sys/kernel/debug/stop_machine/trigger_dump
  Calls stopper_deadlock_dump() with synthetic data — prints the full
  diagnostic output to dmesg WITHOUT calling panic(). Use this to verify
  the dump format, symbol resolution (%pS), cpumask printing, and
  trigger_all_cpu_backtrace() IPI delivery. Safe, non-destructive.

TEST 2: debugfs "simulate_deadlock" trigger — calls panic()
  Write any value to:
    /sys/kernel/debug/stop_machine/simulate_panic
  Runs a real stop_machine() with a callback that sleeps past the 3s
  timeout. This fires the REAL detection path including panic(). Use on a
  test device where you want to verify the full ramdump capture flow.
  WARNING: this WILL crash the device and trigger a ramdump.

TEST 3: module parameter override for timeout (reduce for faster testing)
  Boot with:
    stopper_timeout_sec=1
  or at runtime (before test):
    echo 1 > /sys/module/stop_machine/parameters/stopper_timeout_sec
  Reduces the 3s timeout to 1s so stress-ng tests complete faster.

Stress-ng test procedure (using TEST 3):
  # Reduce timeout to 1s for faster iteration
  echo 1 > /sys/module/stop_machine/parameters/stopper_timeout_sec
  # Run scheduler stress to trigger active load balancing
  stress-ng --sched 4 --sched-ops 1000000 &
  stress-ng --affinity 4 --affinity-ops 100000 &
  # Or use hackbench
  hackbench -g 8 -l 10000

